</noscript></center><div class='main'><div class='mainheader'><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="2925d4451d5574ccd21dc30532bb756d" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></div><div class='maincontent'><BR><font class="h1font"> Results of 1st DeckTech AAM Contest!<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/wars/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/wars/main/mpage.php?member=17'>Neal "Dredlox" Razi</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/wars/main/mpage.php?member=17&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 27, 2006</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> These turned out to be very close games, which is a testament to the strength of The Perfect Army, since the rival team was almost like a counter to this team.  Surprisingly, I felt the Brumbar was the critical piece to use for the win, along with of course the sniper.<br />
<br />
Overall, I found the Perfect Army a team that requires a great amount of skill, but rewards that skill in a big way. It&#39;s not a team a newbie can pick up and win with, but when you get used to the nuances it can be really versatile. It has strong legs too, it&#39;s a tough team to beat in short order, or to lose on luck.<br />
<br />
Play notes follow<br />
<br />
Game 1<br />
<br />
On half and half map. One 105 & vet went after the sniper, and the other pair stayed near the obj.  The 105 got headshot, and the brumbar moved in to keep it disrupted until the pgs arrived. The other shermans had to back up, bringing the pgs and pfs near the objective. The brumbar dodged a lot of shots, chased around the other 105 eventually bringing it under assualt by the pgs. The vet shermans could match the points.<br />
<br />
Game 2<br />
<br />
On Urban Combat. The sniper had to blow his headshot on a vet sherman before dying, and the pfs got caught out of position. The near entire squad was caught between 2 pairs, one 105 + 1 vet, on each side of the city, and nuked to death.  Total domination for the shermans.<br />
<br />
Game 3<br />
<br />
on Higher Ground. The best technical game, it turned into a repeat of game 1&#39;s tactics. The sniper got a long range headshot on a 105, and the brumbar ran flush. It kept the 105 disrupted (barely), while all Shermans converged to help out their buddy. A lot of troops died, but the first 105 was taken out.<br />
<br />
This allowed a large contigent of pgs and both pfs to get right and near the obj, and the brumbar proceeded to fearlessly track down the 105. Choosing to remain on task of killing pfs and grenadiers, the 105 eventually took a short range disruption and went down to the pgs. The game was still a draw due to mass kills of nearly everything by the 105s until a pf scored a medium range damage on a disrupted vet sherman, and the brumbar made 3 cover rolls while squatting on the obj. He took out the damaged sherman, and that was game.<br />
<br />
The Brumbar was the complete MVP of game 3.<br />
<br />
Overall, the 105s proved more than worth their weight, killing hordes of hard to eliminate infantry. The pgs were as versatile as ever. The Brumbar was surprisingly useful despite its poor anti armor stats. And the Vet Shermans are the most mobile pieces in the game, but at times fragile.<br />
<br />
The Perfect Army is then the winner of the first DeckTech AAM Team Building Contest! Great work, Ben. <br />
<br />
Thanks to CardAgora and John Arendt for sponsoring such a great contest, and Mike The Judge Blumberg and Danny Derfman Price (Mario Caluzi) for helping with the testing. Look for the next contest soon!<br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/wars/articles/articles.php?id=6380&view=1&PHPSESSID=2925d4451d5574ccd21dc30532bb756d'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/wars/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=2925d4451d5574ccd21dc30532bb756d'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/wars/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=2925d4451d5574ccd21dc30532bb756d'> become a registered member</a></font></div></div>


